    {
      "check_id": "CWE-79",
      "path": "templates/account.html",
      "start": {
        "line": 43,
        "col": 1
      },
      "end": {
        "line": 43,
        "col": 100
      },
      "extra": {
        "message": "Stored XSS via profile_image data URI in account.html\n\nThe profile image is rendered in an `<object>` tag's `data` attribute: `data=\"{{current_user.profile_image.decode() ...}}\"`. The `<object>` tag can render arbitrary content types including HTML with JavaScript. Since the profile_image is user-controlled (uploaded via URL), this can lead to XSS.\n\nImpact: An attacker could set their profile image to a data:text/html URI containing JavaScript, which would execute when the account page is rendered.\n\nFix: Use `<img>` tags instead of `<object>` tags for profile images, or validate that the data URI contains only image MIME types.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-79"
          ],
          "finding_id": "09ae8682-44fa-40fe-9158-98f5b0184821"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "check_id": "CWE-79",
      "path": "templates/base.html",
      "start": {
        "line": 61,
        "col": 1
      },
      "end": {
        "line": 61,
        "col": 100
      },
      "extra": {
        "message": "Stored XSS via profile_image data URI in base.html\n\nThe profile image is rendered as a data URI in an `<object>` tag's `data` attribute: `data=\"{{current_user.profile_image.decode() ...}}\"`. While Jinja2 auto-escapes HTML entities, the `<object>` tag with a `data` attribute can be exploited with specially crafted data URIs (e.g., `data:text/html,...`) to execute JavaScript. The profile_image is stored from a user-controlled URL via SSRF, and the mimetype is guessed from the URL, so an attacker could potentially inject a `data:text/html` payload.\n\nImpact: If an attacker can control the profile_image content (via the SSRF image upload), they could inject a data:text/html URI that executes JavaScript in the context of other users' sessions.\n\nFix: Validate that profile_image data URIs only contain image MIME types. Consider using `<img>` tags instead of `<object>` tags, or implement Content-Security-Policy headers to restrict object sources.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-79"
          ],
          "finding_id": "d731eb39-32c9-4ad7-a36b-d18efcef5c39"
        }
      }
    },
